04742nam a22007695i 9780812290202DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979577567  a97808122902027 a10.9783/97808122902022doi  a(DE-B1597)450997  a(OCoLC)891404391  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a909222/ger1 aSpoerri, Marlene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEngineering Revolution :bThe Paradox of Democracy Promotion in Serbia /cMarlene Spoerri. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Promoting Democracy and Aiding Political Parties Abroad -- t2. The Absence of Aid in Milošević’s Serbia, 1990–1996 -- t3. Preparing for Regime Change, 1997–2000 -- t4. Democracy Promotion in Milošević’s Shadow, 2001–2012 -- t5. Rethinking Aid’s Legacy in Serbia -- tAppendix. List of Interviewees -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe nonviolent overthrow of Balkan dictator Slobodan Milošević in October 2000 is celebrated as democracy promotion at its best. This perceived political success has been used to justify an industry tasked with "exporting" democracy to countries like Belarus, Ukraine, Tunisia, and Egypt. Yet the true extent of the West's involvement in Milošević's overthrow remained unclear until now. Engineering Revolution uses declassified CIA documents and personal interviews with diplomats, aid providers, and policymakers, as well as thousands of pages of internal NGO documents, to explore what proponents consider one of the greatest successes of the democracy promotion enterprise.Through its in-depth examination of the two decades that preceded and followed Milošević's unseating, as well as its critical look at foreign assistance targeting Serbia's troubled political party landscape, Engineering Revolution upends the conventional wisdom on the effectiveness of democracy promotion in Serbia. Marlene Spoerri demonstrates that democracy took root in Serbia in spite of, not because of, Western intervention—in fact, foreign intervention often hurt rather than helped Serbia's tenuous transition to democracy. As Western governments recalibrate their agendas in the wake of the Arab Spring, this timely book offers important lessons for the democracy promotion community as it sets its sights on the Middle East, former Soviet Union, and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2014z9783110370416oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229020240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812290202423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812290202.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-DSWb2014